@node Accessibility
@chapter §18 — Accessibility (Opt-In Mode Layer)

Spacecraft Software applications must be usable by people who navigate by
screen reader, by keyboard alone, or with low vision. This chapter is the
accessibility contract for @strong{all} application classes --- CLI, TUI, and
GUI --- and supersedes §13's design-system framing wherever the two overlap.

@strong{Two-sided rule.} Accessibility support is @strong{mandatory for the
developer to implement} and @strong{optional for the user to activate}:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Every} Spacecraft Software application @strong{other than a project
registered as a game (§18.5)} MUST ship a working accessible mode. This
applies to new and existing projects alike --- there is no
new-projects-only phase-in.
@item
Accessible mode is @strong{off by default}. The default experience is the
@code{Steelbore} theme and standard rendering, entirely unchanged. Enabling
accessibility never becomes a precondition for using the software normally,
and shipping it never degrades the default presentation.
@end itemize

@strong{Normative targets.} @strong{WCAG 2.2 Level AA} where the success
criteria apply, and @strong{EN 301 549 clause 11 (non-web software)} as the
anchor for CLI and TUI applications, which WCAG addresses only indirectly.
Clause 11 is cited because it is the only normative text that speaks to
terminal software; the European Accessibility Act has been enforceable since
2025-06-28.

@menu
* Accessible Mode Activation::
* CLI and TUI Accessibility::
* GUI Accessibility::
* Accessibility Verification::
* Games Carve-Out::
@end menu

@node Accessible Mode Activation
@section §18.1 — Activation

Accessible mode resolves once at startup from four sources. Precedence,
highest first:

@multitable {@strong{4. Auto-detect hints}} {@code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y=1} / @code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y=0} --- the umbrella-wide environment variable}
@headitem
Source
 @tab Form
@item
@strong{1. Command-line flag}
 @tab @code{--accessible} / @code{--no-accessible}
@item
@strong{2. Environment}
 @tab @code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y=1} / @code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y=0} --- the
umbrella-wide environment variable
@item
@strong{3. Configuration}
 @tab @code{[accessibility] enabled = true} in the project's config file
@item
@strong{4. Auto-detect hints}
 @tab @code{TERM=dumb}, @code{NO_COLOR}, or @code{GTK_MODULES} containing
@code{gail:atk}
@end multitable

@itemize
@item
A hint (source 4) @strong{may} enable accessible mode, but must never be
inferred from an ambiguous signal. An explicit @code{--no-accessible} or
@code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y=0} always wins, at every level.
@item
Unset at every source ⇒ @strong{standard @code{Steelbore} rendering,
unchanged}. Silence is never read as consent to change the default
presentation.
@item
The resolved state and the source that decided it must be reported under
@code{--verbose}, so a user can tell why the mode is on or off.
@item
The toggle is a @strong{single switch} governing every behavior in §18.2 and
§18.3 together. Per-feature accessibility flags fragment the contract and are
not a substitute.
@end itemize

@node CLI and TUI Accessibility
@section §18.2 — CLI & TUI Requirements

@strong{The constraint that shapes everything here:} a terminal has no
accessibility tree. There is no ARIA, there are no roles, and there are no
live regions. A screen reader reads the emulator's character grid, so a
redraw-based interface produces re-reads and speech loops rather than useful
speech. Accessibility cannot be delegated to the TUI framework --- no terminal
UI library provides it --- so the application must supply a linear fallback
itself.

@subsection §18.2.1 — Rules that apply in every mode

These are not gated behind the toggle. They are correctness requirements for
all output, always:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Color is never the sole carrier of meaning.} Every colored status
carries a text tag: @code{[OK]}, @code{[ERROR]}, @code{[WARN]},
@code{[INFO]}. A red line that says only "failed to connect" is
non-compliant; @code{[ERROR] failed to connect} is compliant.
@item
@strong{No text on colored fills} unless that specific pair is verified per
§11 --- palette tokens are verified against Void Navy, not against each
other.
@item
@strong{Diagnostics go to @code{stderr}}, results to @code{stdout}, and the
two are never interleaved into one visual block.
@item
@strong{@code{NO_COLOR}, @code{FORCE_COLOR}, @code{CLICOLOR}, and
@code{TERM=dumb}} are honored with the precedence already defined by the
@code{spacecraft-cli-standard} skill.
@end itemize

@subsection §18.2.2 — Rules that apply in accessible mode

@multitable {@strong{No decorative art}} {Spinners, marquees, blinking text, and progress animations are replaced by a single static line carrying monotonic progress}
@headitem
Requirement
 @tab Rule
@item
@strong{No animation}
 @tab Spinners, marquees, blinking text, and progress animations are
replaced by a single static line carrying monotonic progress
(@code{Working@dots{} 40%}), rewritten at most once per second
@item
@strong{No decorative art}
 @tab ASCII art, banners, box-drawing decoration, and figlet headers are
suppressed. Where the art is @emph{informational} (a diagram, a chart),
emit an equivalent text description instead --- do not simply drop it
@item
@strong{Linear output}
 @tab Output is append-only and reads correctly top-to-bottom. Blank lines
separate logical sections so a screen reader can navigate by paragraph
@item
@strong{Tabular fallback}
 @tab Any table offers a non-columnar rendering --- one
@code{field: value} pair per line --- since column alignment conveys
nothing through speech
@item
@strong{Prompt legibility}
 @tab Interactive prompts state the question, the available choices, and
the default in plain text before awaiting input. Prompts that rely on
cursor positioning or redraw to convey state are non-compliant
@end multitable

@subsection §18.2.3 — TUI linear mode

Any full-screen TUI MUST additionally provide a @strong{non-redraw,
append-only stream mode}, reachable through the same §18.1 toggle. In linear
mode the application writes new state as new lines rather than repainting
regions, and does not take over the alternate screen buffer.

Where a TUI would otherwise be the only way to perform an operation, an
equivalent @strong{non-interactive CLI path} must exist --- flags plus
@code{--json} output --- so the operation remains scriptable and reachable
without navigating a visual grid. Per §8, this path must be documented in the
project's Texinfo manual alongside the interactive one.

@node GUI Accessibility
@section §18.3 — GUI Requirements

Graphical applications expose an accessibility tree to the platform's
assistive-technology API. Which bridge to use depends on how the UI is drawn:

@multitable {@strong{Rust, custom-drawn UI}} {@strong{AccessKit} (Apache-2.0) --- one API over UI Automation (Windows), NSAccessibility (macOS), and AT-SPI (Linux)}
@headitem
UI stack
 @tab Required bridge
@item
@strong{Rust, custom-drawn UI}
 @tab @strong{AccessKit} (Apache-2.0) --- one API over UI Automation
(Windows), NSAccessibility (macOS), and AT-SPI (Linux). Already integrated
in egui, Slint, Bevy, Freya, Xilem, and winit
@item
@strong{GTK 4}
 @tab @code{GtkAccessible} --- WAI-ARIA roles and states surfaced over
AT-SPI
@item
@strong{Flutter}
 @tab @code{Semantics} widgets and @code{SemanticsRole}
@item
@strong{Qt}
 @tab @code{QAccessible}
@end multitable

Custom-drawn widgets are the failure case to watch: a canvas-rendered control
is invisible to assistive technology unless the application publishes its
role and state explicitly. This is precisely the gap AccessKit exists to
close, which is why it is required rather than merely suggested for Rust GUI
work (§3.1 already makes Rust the preferred language).

@strong{Requirements:}

@itemize
@item
Every interactive element carries an explicit accessible @strong{name} and
@strong{role}. Purely decorative elements are explicitly marked decorative
so they are skipped rather than read as noise.
@item
State changes that matter to the user are @strong{announced}, not merely
repainted.
@item
System preferences for @strong{reduced motion} and @strong{high contrast}
are honored --- these are read from the platform, independently of the §18.1
toggle, because the user has already expressed the preference system-wide.
@item
Keyboard reachability and focus visibility follow §10.
@end itemize

@node Accessibility Verification
@section §18.4 — Verification & Remediation

@strong{Verification.} An accessibility claim is not satisfied by inspection.
Before a release:

@itemize
@item
@strong{CLI/TUI:} pipe the accessible-mode output through a speech
synthesizer (e.g. @code{espeak-ng}) and confirm it is comprehensible when
heard rather than seen. Confirm the non-interactive path completes the same
operations as the interactive one.
@item
@strong{GUI:} exercise the application with a real screen reader --- Orca on
Linux, NVDA on Windows, VoiceOver on macOS --- and confirm every interactive
element announces a name and a role.
@item
@strong{Contrast:} measure the actual pairings used, not just
foreground-on-background, and record the ratios (§11).
@item
@strong{Keyboard:} complete every primary task without a pointing device.
@end itemize

@strong{Remediation for existing projects.} §18 applies to every project
immediately on adoption of v1.33, which means projects predating it are
non-compliant until retrofitted. This is stated plainly rather than softened
into a recommendation. Until a project conforms, it MUST carry a
@strong{dated remediation entry} in @code{PROJECTS.md} recording its current
accessibility state and the intended remediation. An absent entry is a
compliance failure in its own right --- a project may be unfinished, but it
may not be silently unfinished. @strong{Projects registered as games (§18.5)
are excluded} --- they owe no remediation entry, because they owe no
conformance.

@node Games Carve-Out
@section §18.5 — Games Carve-Out

@strong{Projects registered as games are exempt from §18 in full and from
§10 in full.} Accessibility features in a game are @strong{optional}: none
is required, nothing is enforced, and their absence is never a compliance
failure. A game may ship an elaborate accessibility suite, a single option,
or nothing at all --- entirely at the maintainer's discretion (§5.4).

@strong{Rationale:} §18 is built on CLI, TUI, and GUI assumptions --- a
character grid, or a widget tree with roles and names. Games satisfy
neither. They are real-time simulations rendering custom, non-widget
interfaces where play itself is the purpose, and the accessibility
techniques that suit them (remappable controls, colorblind-safe signalling,
subtitles, difficulty options) are a different discipline from the one §18
codifies. Mandating §18 on a game would enforce the wrong requirements at
disproportionate cost.

This is the @strong{only} carve-out in §18, and it is narrow: it applies to
projects registered below, not to any project that merely has a playful or
game-like interface.

@subsection §18.5.1 — Declaration & Registry

A project is a game for the purposes of this Standard when @strong{both}
hold --- the same declaration-plus-registry pattern as the §5.3 general-use
carve-out:

@itemize
@item
The declaration appears in the project's @code{README.md}, alongside the
§5.2 posture section.
@item
The project is listed in the registry below.
@end itemize

@strong{Games registry} (keep in sync with @code{PROJECTS.md} and the §2.1
registry):

@multitable {(all other projects)} {@strong{Game} --- exempt from §18 and §10}
@headitem
Project
 @tab Class
@item
Ironway
 @tab @strong{Game} --- exempt from §18 and §10
@item
(all other projects)
 @tab Standard --- §18 and §10 apply in full
@end multitable

@subsection §18.5.2 — Recommended for Games (never required)

The following are @strong{suggestions}, offered because they are
low-cost and widely expected in games. A game may adopt any, all, or none
of them; declining is not a compliance failure and needs no justification:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Remappable controls} --- already standard practice in games,
independent of accessibility.
@item
@strong{Leave screen-reader chords alone} --- @kbd{Insert},
@kbd{CapsLock}, @kbd{KP_Insert}, and @kbd{Ctrl}+@kbd{Option} are claimed by
NVDA, Orca, and VoiceOver. Capturing them collides with a screen reader the
player may be running.
@item
@strong{Colorblind-safe signalling} --- pair hue with shape, icon, or text
so status does not rest on color alone.
@item
@strong{Subtitles and captions} for spoken or plot-critical audio.
@item
@strong{Honor the system reduced-motion preference} where the engine
exposes it.
@end itemize

@subsection §18.5.3 — Shared Vocabulary

If a game @emph{chooses} to ship an accessibility toggle, it should use the
§18.1 names (@code{--accessible}, @code{SPACECRAFT_A11Y}) and the §11.1.1
theme-variant names rather than inventing its own. This constrains only the
@emph{naming} of features the game already decided to build --- it requires
no feature to exist, and adds nothing to the exemption above.

